Use MAUI's `#if` platform directives combined with the standard DI container in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- Place each implementation under `Platforms/<platform>/` (e.g., `Platforms/Android/AndroidNotificationService.cs`). Those files are already conditionally compiled per-platform via the default `.csproj` settings.
- The `#if` directives (`ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS`) are defined automatically by the MAUI build targets — no manual setup needed.
- This won't break on any platform because only the matching branch compiles. No unresolvable type references remain in the final binary.
- Inject `INotificationService` via constructor injection anywhere you need it.
